Question 2¶

A)

I subsetted the following variables: [HalfBath, FullBath, BsmtFullBath, GarageCars, ExterQual, KitchenQual, CentralAir, and PavedDrive].

For the quantitative variables HalfBath, FullBath, BsmtFullBath, and GarageCars, my rationale is as follows:

HalfBath, FullBath, and BsmtFullBath show positive correlation in the constructed heatmap below, and can effectively account for mist other measures of room quantitiy and living space (e.g. TotRmsAbvGrd, GrLivingSpace, etc.).

GarageCars shows positive correlation, while also effectively accounting for GarageArea. Generally, the more cars a garage can hold the large it will tend to be.

For the categorical variables:

ExterQual and KitchenQual helps break up the more comprehensive OverallQual, while helping to narrow our focus on the effect of two critical factors for a property's sale price. I believe the quality of the exterior trumps the actual material, while the quality of the kitchen - which can be a centerpiece of the property - better accounts for the weight of the kitchen on price (as most properties listed only have 1 kitchen).

CentralAir is a crucial factor for property price, since weather in Ames, Iowa can reach below freezing. Not having the capacity for central heating could crater the asking price of a property due to the cost of future installation.

PavedDrive allows us to account for potentially unfinished or in-progress properties, while also accounting for the negative effect of an unpaved (e.g. Dirt, gravel, etc.) road on a property's price.

Question 3¶

A)

Looking at the histogram and QQ plot below, the distribution of SalePrice appears to be mostly normal, but with a slight skew. Specifically, this skew in the distribution seems to be most apparent past the 1st positive quantile - although the skew is also marginally present past the 1st negative qunatile, as well.

B)

I believe some form of transformation would be appropriate for SalePrice. If we can adjust it to a more normal distribution, then we can more easily fulfill an assumption of normality when performing confidence intervals and tests of significance. If we choose not to adjust SalePrice, then we might risk constructing statistical instruments that provide misleading interpretations.

C)

A Box-Cox transformation provided a $\lambda$ of $\approx$ -0.0769.

(See below for plots)

Question 4¶

A)

Intercept coefficient:

A property with no half-/full bathrooms above grade, no full bathrooms below grade, no garage, excellent exterior and kitchen quality, no paved/partially-paved drive, and no central air would hold a price of $e^{11.7169}$ $\approx$ $122,626.69

Quantitative coefficients:

HalfBath: A marginal 1-unit change = $\Delta$ 10.35% in SalePrice

FullBath: A marginal 1-unit change = $\Delta$ 19.92% in SalePrice

BsmtFullBath: A marginal 1-unit change = $\Delta$ 11.34% in SalePrice

GarageCars: A marginal 1-unit change = $\Delta$ 14.48% in SalePrice

Categorical exterior quality coefficients:

ExterQual_Fa: $\Delta$ -44.07% in SalePrice compared to an excellent (Ex) exterior quality

ExterQual_Gd: $\Delta$ -16.57% in SalePrice compared to an excellent (Ex) exterior quality

ExterQual_TA: $\Delta$ -28.51% in SalePrice compared to an excellent (Ex) exterior quality

Categorial kitchen quality coefficients:

KitchenQual_Fa: $\Delta$ -29.87% in SalePrice compared to an excellent (Ex) kitchen quality

KitchenQual_Gd: $\Delta$ -20.70% in SalePrice compared to an excellent (Ex) kitchen quality

KitchenQual_TA: $\Delta$ -30.26% in SalePrice compared to an excellent (Ex) kitchen quality

Categorical paved drive coefficients:

PavedDrive_P: $\Delta$ 10.97% in SalePrice compared to no (N) paved drive

PavedDrive_Y: $\Delta$ 8.57% in SalePrice compared to no (N) paved drive

Categorical central air coefficients:

CentralAir_Y: $\Delta$ 22.03% in SalePrice compared to no (N) central heating

$R^{2}:$

The constructed model accounts for 73.80% of the variance seen within the data.

Tests of significance:

As the p-value for all regression coefficients < $\alpha$ = 0.05, we can - with 95% confidence - reject {$H_{0}$: $\beta_{0,1,...,13}$ = 0} in favor of our constructed coefficients.

B)

For my higher order terms, I chose to place GarageCars to a higher order to represent the increasing relationship of GarageCars on SalePrice with decreasing marginal effects past GarageCars = 3.

For my interactions effects, I included the relationship between the like-like dummy variables of KitchenQual and ExterQual to represent the positive correlation between a similar kitchen quality and external quality.

C)

Due to the Jarque-Bera test providing a large test statistic and a p $\approx$ 0 < $\alpha$ $\approx$ 0.01 (given the sample size of 1460), we can reject {$H_{0}$: The residuals of the MR on log(SalePrice) are normally distributed} in favor of {$H_{1}$: The residuals of the MR on log(SalePrice) are not normally distributed}.
